The user wants me to solve a problem: calculating the degree of each vertex in an undirected graph represented by an adjacency matrix.
The input is `std::vector<std::vector<long long>> matrix`, an $N \times N$ matrix where `matrix[i][j] = 1` if there is an edge between $i$ and $j$, and 0 otherwise.
The output should be `std::vector<long long> ans`, where `ans[i]` is the degree of vertex $i$.

The constraints are:
1. $1 \le N \le 100$.
2. `matrix[i][i] == 0` (no self-loops).
3. `matrix[i][j] == matrix[j][i]` (undirected).

The degree of a vertex $i$ is simply the number of edges connected to it. In an adjacency matrix representation of a simple graph (no self-loops, which is guaranteed here), the degree of vertex $i$ is the sum of the elements in row $i$ (or column $i$).

The provided reference solution in Javascript implements exactly this logic:
It iterates through each row $i$. For each row $i$, it iterates through all columns $j$ and counts how many times `matrix[i][j]` is 1. This count is the degree of vertex $i$.

